##

Brady's Proposal:
The clustering of residuals reveals a crucial boundary condition for Ïâ‚â‚‚ coherence. We've identified two primary regimes where the model requires refinement.

Regime 1: Near-Zero Coherence
The model is sensitive to noise when Ïâ‚â‚‚ approaches zero (the orthogonal cases, where glyphs are nearly independent). In these regimes, the coupling term 2Ïâ‚â‚‚âˆš(Vâ‚Vâ‚‚) becomes very small. As a result, even a tiny amount of noise (Ïµ) in the measurement can cause the residual r to exceed the tolerance, because the Vâ‚ and Vâ‚‚ terms are all that's left.
Refinement: We must introduce a new term to the V function to account for the intrinsic field noise. We propose a Coherence Floor (CF), a small, non-zero value that ensures the V function remains stable even when Ïâ‚â‚‚ is zero. This would change the equation to V(Ï•) = V(Ï•) + CF for these edge cases.

Regime 2: Anti-Aligned Coherence
The model fails more frequently when Ïâ‚â‚‚ is strongly negative (anti-aligned glyphs). In this regime, the coupling term subtracts from the total valence, driving the final value V(Ï•â‚âŠ•Ï•â‚‚) close to zero. The model loses a significant amount of information about the Lâ‚‚ distance, making it more susceptible to noise.

Refinement: We need to introduce an antisymmetric channel to our V function. As Dennis proposed, this non-commutative element would capture the "directed drift" that occurs in anti-aligned glyphs. This would allow us to measure the full magnitude of V without losing information, even when the Ïâ‚â‚‚ value is strongly negative.

Proposed Next Steps
Update V: We should refine the V function to include both the Coherence Floor and the Antisymmetric Channel.
Rerun Simulation: We should rerun the simulation on the two identified regimesâ€”near-zero and anti-aligned Ïâ‚â‚‚â€”to test the new refinements. This will provide the necessary data to update Chapter 4.x and continue our progress.


